4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT REVISING LAWS RELATED TO HOME INSPECTIONS;
5 ALIGNING THE HOME INSPECTION PROGRAM WITH OTHER DEPARTMENTAL LICENSING PROGRAMS;
6 PROVIDING DEFINITIONS; PROVIDING FEES; PROVIDING RULEMAKING AUTHORITY; REVISING LAW
7 RELATED TO HOME INSPECTION LICENSURE; PROVIDING STANDARDS FOR THE PRACTICE OF
8 HOME INSPECTIONS; AMENDING SECTIONS 37-1-401, 39-9-101, 39-9-102, 39-9-206, 39-9-207, 39-9-301,
9 AND 39-9-303, MCA; REPEALING SECTIONS 39-9-212 AND 39-9-213, MCA; AND PROVIDING A DELAYED
10 EFFECTIVE DATE.”
11
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
13
14 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Definitions. As used in [sections 1 through 4], the following definitions
15 apply:
16 (1) "Department" means the department of labor and industry.
17 (2) (a) "Home inspection" means a physical examination of a residential dwelling to identify major
18 defects in various attributes of or attachments to the dwelling, including mechanical, electrical, and plumbing
19 systems in addition to structural and other essential components. Home inspections are performed for
20 compensation and employ visual observation and the testing of user controls but not mathematical or
21 specialized engineering sciences.
22 (b) The term does not mean a physical examination of a residential dwelling when the owner or a
23 representative of the owner requests the examination by an individual who is licensed in this state and acting
24 within the scope of practice of the individual's profession or occupation.
25 (3) "Home inspection report" means a written document prepared by a home inspector for a client
26 and issued to the client in exchange for compensation after a home inspection has been completed. The report
27 must clearly identify and describe:
28 (a) the inspected systems, structures, and other relevant components of the dwelling;
